snippet.textDisplay:
It seems you're totally missing the point of this particular CPU. It is meant for a really small budget rig. Paired with a cheap A320 board you can build a total system for under 200 USD and use it for everyday tasks like surfing, office etc. The big plus it gives you is the capabililty to at least play some games at minimal settings and 720p resolution for instance. later on you could potentially upgrade the PC with a dedicated GPU. When I would be a high school student today I would really appreciate the possibility to gradually build a rig step by step as budget permits. Starting with a B350 board an 8GB stick of RAM would be sensible (Then you could later upgrade another 8G RAM, 1650 GPU and Ryzen 5-1600 CPU...and have a nice allround PC...).


Well just my 2 cents...

I think the Ryzen 5 3600 should be the standard for anybody wanting to build a budget or mid-range gaming PC. If your budget is really limited when it comes to graphics card options, you can go with the GTX 1650 Super (for less than the price of your CPU) for some solid 1080p gaming. The Ryzen 5 3600 will give you plenty of time to upgrade to a better graphics card down the line while keeping your CPU.

snippet.textDisplay:
Why do so many of these channels not understand that a 'budget' build means a build for people who really can't afford to simply add an extra $/£50? I work full time and use older hardware (6950X/1080Ti) but it's working fine. My 12-year-old brother has been saving up for nearly 10 months to buy a new PC with some old parts of mine, so adding an extra $/£50 is not an option. And I live in a wealthy nation (UK), but just look at the average monthly salaries of these European countries (USD): UK: ~$3,700, France: ~$3,300, Germany: ~$4,400, Romania: ~$450, Moldova: ~$340 (not typos for Romania and Moldova). The system in this video would take the average Moldovan nearly two months to save up for without food, rent, bills, or anything else (inc. taxes).


A budget build should be, broadly speaking, under 300 and include a combination of new current and last gen hardware with a stated resolution (for gaming). Just going onto pcpartpicker provides a tonne of options (including 2x4GB for cheaper than the 1x8GB shown in this video at the same speed - seriously, why use single channel?).
